		<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="li-comment-390118">
		<div id="comment-390118">
			<div class="comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/7a7054811b34beefd050ed0da3a2aeb7?s=40&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/7a7054811b34beefd050ed0da3a2aeb7?s=80&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' />				<cite class="fn">Anonymous</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>			</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->
				
			<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="index.html#comment-390118">
				May 11, 2015 at 07:02					</a>
									</div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->

				<div class="comment-body"><p>Now that we&#8217;ve had a few weeks to all calm down, could I moot an idea that might, just might, actually help bring the Hugos back to legitimacy and stop all the nastiness without infringing on the free speech rights of the right-wing factions (whatever they choose to call themselves right now) but also not further tarnish the reputation of one of the only really respectable fan-voted awards in the world?</p>
<p>&#8220;Slate&#8221; voting, as it stands, doesn&#8217;t break any bylaws, like it or not. But it&#8217;s also stacking the ballot in ways that don&#8217;t reflect the preferences of the majority of readers (just compare with, say, the Nebula ballot, or the way most voters who don&#8217;t nominate plan to vote). Could there be just a little constitutional amendment stating that, while anyone may promote a work that he/she has actually written or otherwise produced for a Hugo, no one may promote someone else&#8217;s work in a public way? So in other words, individual authors could alert their readers to their eligible works on their blogs (and give helpful information like which length category they belong in), but no one can realistically assemble a Slate unless it&#8217;s such an obviously navel-gazing Slate (since it&#8217;s all the work of one author) that no one will take it seriously?</p>
<p>Might this be a way to cut the Gordian knot? Doesn&#8217;t take away the right wing&#8217;s nomination privileges.</p>
</div>

